---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Systems Thinking Principles · Founder-Built Execution"
  description="The principles behind building reliable, maintainable internal systems: ownership, stability, documentation, and responsible evolution."
>
  <section style="padding: 80px 24px; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 24px;">Principles</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 64px;">
      The thinking behind the systems.
    </p>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom: 16px;">
        1. Ownership vs. Delegation in Systems
      </h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        Delegation works for tasks with clear boundaries. Systems—especially internal ones—have fluid boundaries. What starts as a reporting tool becomes a decision engine, then integrates with operations, then needs real-time updates.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        Ownership means one person understands the whole, sees connections before they become problems, and evolves the system intentionally rather than reactively.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom: 16px;">
        2. Why Stability Precedes Scale
      </h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        A system that works reliably for 10 users but fails unpredictably for 100 is worse than one that works for 5 users consistently. Scale reveals architectural flaws, but instability destroys trust.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        We build for the current reality plus one order of magnitude. When that's stable, we scale again. Not before.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom: 16px;">
        3. When Spreadsheets Fail (and What Comes Next)
      </h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        Spreadsheets are perfect until they're not. The failure signals: multiple people editing, version confusion, manual data entry errors, formulas breaking silently, decision delays waiting for "the spreadsheet person."
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        The next step isn't a bigger spreadsheet. It's a system with: single source of truth, controlled access, automated data flows, validation, and audit trails.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom: 16px;">
        4. Building for Daily Use, Not Demos
      </h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        Demo-ware is optimized for first impressions. Production systems are optimized for the 1000th use. This means: loading states, error recovery, data validation, performance under real data volumes, clear error messages, and intuitive workflows for tired users at 4 PM.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 24px; color: #f0f0f5; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom: 16px;">
        5. Responsible Evolution (Not Scope Creep)
      </h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        Systems evolve or die. But evolution without architecture is cancer—features added wherever they fit, complexity growing exponentially.
      </p>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.7;">
        Responsible evolution means: understanding the cost of each feature, preserving conceptual integrity, and saying "not now" more often than "yes."
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="background: #1a1a23; border: 1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius: 8px; padding: 32px; margin-top: 64px;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 16px; color: #f0f0f5;">These principles guide every system we build.</h2>
      <p style="color: #b0b0c0; line-height: 1.6;">
        They're not abstract philosophy—they're practical constraints that produce better outcomes. If your challenge aligns with this thinking, we should talk.
      </p>
      <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 32px;">
        <a href="/contact" style="background: #3a8bba; color: white; padding: 16px 32px; border-radius: 4px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.1rem; display: inline-block;">Start the Conversation</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
